{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00222254711/1930070201/0383.xml":{"full_text":"Selling Expected to Continue Through Tomorrow, the Spectator Believes\nBROKERS LIGHTEN HOLDINGS\nFOR JULY 4 HOLIDAY\nBuying of Sound Stocks Now for Possible\nRallies Next Week to Be Profitable,\nExpert Contends\nBy THE SPECTATOR\nTomorrow\u2019s stock market session will be the last before the\nFourth of July holiday. Therefore, it is to be expected that\nthe selling that appeared in the market yesterday afternoon\nwill continue up to tomorrow\u2019s close. Short-lived rallies may\ncome and go today and tomorrow, but in general I think\noperators will lighten their commitments for the weekend.\nCertainly there can be no incentive toward bullish operations,\nwith the market closing and the business outlook uncertain.\nI believe traders would be safe in buying stocks today and\ntomorrow, in anticipation of rallies early next week. I think\nsuch trades would result profitably. But. in view of the business\nsituation and the fact that bearish news development over the\nweek-end might upset the market. I would recommend a policy\nof watchful waiting for the next few days.\nPool Operations\nMarket fluctuations prohibited\npool operations, except in rare\nInstances where special develop\nments made it possible to give a\nparticular issue a run-up. The\nt improved tone that appeared\nMonday, however, encouraged pool\ngroups to resume their work, and\nseveral of them were planning\nyesterday to begin whirling their\nfavorites. In the event that the\nmarket continues in a trading\nrange, instead of slipping into\na further gradual decline, the\npools will take a prominent part\nin trading.\nDespite current reports, United\nCorporation is not buying Con-\nsolidated Gas shares. This rumor,\nhaving been repeated some scores\nof times, has grown tiresome.\nRails In Demand\nOne of the most constructive\nfeatures of yesterday\u2019s session was\nthe early demand for high-grade\nInvestment rails, most of which\nmoved up 1 to 6 points. Atchi\nson, New York Central, Balti\nmore and Ohio, Union Pacific,\nPennsylvania and Canadian Pa-\nciflc were well bought, indicating\nthat those who can afford to buy\nsuch stocks are convinced that\nthe worst of the decline in freight\ntraffic is over. New Haven, one\nof the leading semi-speculative\nrails, is well taken on all reces\nsions.\nYesterday\u2019s late decline was\nexactly in line with this depart\nments prediction that all rallies\nat this time would be temporary\nand purely technical.\nSteel Lacks Support\nDespite claims that high-grade\nstocks are getting good support,\nU. S. Steel, which was easily the\nleader yesterday tumbled from\n161 to 156% as soon as the bears\nbegan operations, and closed at\nlid Hales\nHITBYROME\nROME, July 2 (I.N.S.).\u2014\u201cAmtr\nlean automobile sales in Italy,\nwhich have lately been increasing,\nwill be shut off,\" a statement\nissued at the General Motors Cor\nporation agency here today said\nin commenting on the new retalia\ntory duties imposed by the Italian\ngovernment.\nThe government, taking the\nfirst step in an onslaught against\nthe new American tariffs, in\ncreased the duties on American\nautomobiles imported into Italy\nfrom 100 to 600 per cent. Trucks\nand spare parts were hit as well\nas pleasure cars.\nThe new rates offered a direct\nand dangerous threat against the\nAmerican automobile trade with\nItaly, and grave concern was felt\namong American importers over\nthe possibility of other retaliatory\nrate increases on American\nproducts.\nReserveSecurityLoans Off;\nOther Borrowings Gain\nThe Federal Reserve Board\u2019s\ncondition statement of weekly re\nporting member banks in leading\ncities on June 25 shows increases\nfor the week of $22,000,000 in\nloans and investments, $45,000,000\nin time deposits and $10,000,000\nin borrowings from Federal Re\nserve banks and a decrease of\n$84,000,000 in net demand de\nposits.\nLoans on securities, which at\nall reporting banks were $128,000,-\n000 below the preceding week\u2019s\ntotal, declined $47,000,000 in the\nNew York district, $43,000,000 in\nthe Chicago district, $17,000,000\nIn the San Francisco district, sll,-\n000,000 in the Richmond district,\n$7,000,000 in the Philadelphia dis\ntrict and $6,000,000 in the Dallas\nMHSHINBTON I INaiuAINMCIAL NEWS\nthe day's low, leading most of\nthe list downward. It becomes\nincreasingly apparent that the\nmoney powers are content to let\nthe market drift as it will, at\nleast until the November lows\nare threatened by leading stocks.\nThe weekly report on crude oil\nproduction, showing a gain of\nmore than 30,000 barrels in the\ndaily average, is no help to the\noil price situation.\nMontgomery Ward Sales\nWall Street was pleasantly sur\nprised by the gain of 9.2 per cent\nin Montgomery Wards may sales.\nExpansion of the company\u2019s re\ntail chain was largely responsible\nfor the excellent showing. It will\nbe interesting to see the reports\nof Sears-Roebuck, Woolworth and\nother leaders in the merchandis\ning field. The bullish effect of\nthe \u201cmow\" report was in no way\noffset by the 24 per cent decline\nin May sales of National Bellas\nHess.\nIt is some time since there has\nbeen a report of sale of a Stock\nExchange seat. It is said that\nthree sales have been made, how\never without publicity. One seat\nis reported for sale at $375,000\nwith no bids. Margin business is\nno gold mine these days.\nSelling On Rallies\nWe were surprised yesterday\nwhen one brokerage house, in its\ndaily letter to clients, advised\nshort sales on good rallies. It is\na long time since we have read\nany such advice from brokers.\nSince the beginning of the bull\nmarket a couple of years ago, we\nhad practically decided that such\nadvice never again would be\nwritten. But now we have it\nand it indicates the feeling of a\ncertain sector of the financial\ncommunity in regard to the im\nmediate outlook for the market.\nGENTLIoi\nNETS 53.02\nIn a statement of condition the\nCentral Hanover Bank and Trust\nCompany shows earnings for the\nsix months ended Juhe 30 of\n$3,168,419, or $3.02 a share on\n1,050,000 shares. Dividends de\nclared during the period amounted\nto $3 a share. Earnings for the\nsame period last year are In\ndeterminable because of the mer\nger with the Central Union Trust\nCompany. Book value of the\npresent S2O par value shares is\nSIOO, against $95 a year ago.\nChemical Bank\nStatement of condition as is\nsued by the Chemical Bank and\nTrust Company today indicates\nearnings for the six months\nended June 30 of $1,965,000 or\n$1.31 a share on 1,500 shares of\n$lO par. value. Earnings for the\n12 months ended June 30 were\nequal to $2.91 a share. Earnings\nfor the six months ended June\n30, 1929, were indeterminable on\naccount of the merger with the\nU. S. Mortgage and Trust Com\npany.\ndistrict. \u201cAll other\u201d loans in\ncreased $55,000,000 in the New\nYork district. $6,000,000 in the\nPhiladelphia district and $59,000,-\n000 at all reporting banks, and\ndeclined $19,000,000 in the Chi\ncago district.\nHoldings of U. S. Government\nsecurities increased $31,000,000 in\nthe New York district and $28,-\n000,000 at all reporting banks.\nHoldings of other securities in\ncreased $40,000,000 in the New\nYork district, $9,000,000 in the\nChicago district, and $64,000,000\nat all reporting banks.\nThe principal changes in bor\nrowings from Federal Reserve\nBanins for the week were in\ncreases of $7,000,000 each at the\nFederal Reserve Banks of New\nYork and Cleveland.\nTHE -WASHINGTON TIMES\nI Announces\n\nr rdi\nL liH\n\u2014Times Staff Photo\nANDREW W. MELLON\nSECRETARY OF the Treas\nury, who yesterday announced\nthat the United States closed\nthe 1930 fiscal year with a sur\nplus of $184,000,000. This in\ncluded a number of large obliga\n.tions paid by.foreign govern-,\nments in cash.\nDll PONT EARNS\n51.31ASHARE\nIn a preliminary report issued\nthree weeks in advance of the\nusual date, the E. I. du Pont de\nNemours Company today estima\nted earnings for the quarter ended\nJune 30 at $15,418,000, against\n$16,296,500 in the corresponding\n1929 quarter or $1.31 on the com\nmon against $1.44 last year. The\nreport was Issued early this year,\nit was explained, \u201cfor the gui\ndance and information of stock\nholders who have rights to sub\nscribe to 357,071 shares of the\ncommon stock of the company at\nSBO a share.\" These rights will\nexpire on July 15, before the pub\nlication of the regular official\nquarterly statement.\nFederal Light\nFederal Light and Traction and\nsubsidiaries report for the 12\nmonths May 31 a net profit of\n$2,126,290, against $2,060,738 in\nthe preceding 12 months. Net\nprofit for May totaled $159,534,\nagainst $156,685 in May, 1929.\nBaltimore Gas\nConsolidated Gas and Electric\nLight Company of Baltimore re\nports for the year ended May 31\na net income of $7,711,457,\nagainst $6,626,676 in the preced\ning year.\nEastern Minn. Power\nEastern Minnesota Power Co.\nreports gross income after general\nexpenses and taxes for the year\nended May 31 of $147,392, against\n$122,000 in the year previous.\nWestmoreland Water\nWestmoreland Water Co. re\nports net Income for the year\nended April 30 of $227,854.\nCurtis Manufacturing\nCurtis Manufacturing Co. in\nthe year ended May 31 reports\nnet earnings equivalent to $3.62\na share, against $3.86 a share in\nthe preceding year.\nFidelity Trust\nThe Fidelity Trust Co. today\nchanged its name to the Marine\nMidland Corp., and increased its\ncapital and surplus from $10,000,-\n000 to $20,000,000, it was an\nnounced by James G. Blaine,\npresident.\nThe name change was made in\norder to identify the bank more\nclosely with the Marine Midland\ngroup of sixteen New York State\nbanks, with which it became af\nfiliated last April, and the in\ncrease in the capital and surplus\nis in line with the announced\npolicy of the Marine Midland\nCorporation to develop the New\nYork city unity of the group.\nN. Y. Trust\nNew York Trust Company state\nment of condition indicates earn\nings of $2,661,000 during the six\nmonths ended June 30. equal to\n$5.32 a share on 500,000 shares;\ndividend requirements for entire\nyear are $5 a share\u2014their earn\nings compare with $11.42 a share\nfor full calendar year of 1929.\nDuring six months the company\ntransferred $5,000,000 to its sur\nplus account from undivided prof\nits, bringing the former to $30,000\nand leaving $5,688,\u201979 in the\nlatter. Book value of $25 par\nvalue stock is $96.39, against $93\nsix months ago.\nKings County Trust\nKings County Trust Co. state\nment of condition as of June 30\nindicates earnings during first\nsix months of 1930 of $263,000.\nequal to $52.60 a share on $5,000\nshares outstanding, or at rate of\n$105.20 a share annually.\nThis compares with $81.20 a\nshare earned in six months ended\nJune 29 last year. For 12 months\nended December 31, 1929, earn\nings were equal to $195.48 a\nshare. The company pays SBO in\nregular dividends annually and\npaid an extra of $25 a share on\nNovember 1 last.\nTreasury Faces Needy/\nOs Meeting U. S. Debts\nWith Federal Bills\nWith prospects of heavily re\nduced receipts during the 1931\nfiscal year, the Treasury is faced\nwith the necessity of meeting ma\nturing obligations amounting to\n$1,420,170,500 in certificates and\nbills.\nIn addition, three blocks of\n$1,616,115,500 in 3'/a per cent\nTreasury notes, which may be\ncalled on six months\u2019 notice at\nany of the tax payment periods\nduring the year, must be retired\nin 1932.\nIn the next two years there are\nsecurities of $4,979,928,250 matur\ning or callable, including the first\nLiberty loan of 1932-1947. The\nmajor portion of this issue bears\n3\u2019i per cent, but there is a block\nof over half a billion dollars with\ninterest of 414 per cent, and if the\nusual course is pursued, the bond\nmarket being favorable, this\nblock would be retired and re\nplaced with obligations bearing\nlower interest.\nSecretary Mellon carried over a\nbig cash balance of more than\n$300,000,000 from the 1930 fiscal\nyear because of a maturing block\nof $51,316,000 in Treasury bills\nJuly J 4. another block of $104,-\n600,000 in bilfe August 18, and lhe\nfact that large expenditures may\nbe expected by the Federal Farm\n94,528 BIDWINS\nCHICAGO BONDS\nAward of an issue of $18,970,-\n000 improvement 4 per cent\nbonds was made to Halsey Stuart\n<fc Co., by the city of Chicago.\nThat firm bid 94,528, which was\nslightly higher than a price of\n94,417 tendered by a group\nheaded by the Continental Illi\nnois Company.\nA syndicate had been formed\nby the bankers to market the\nissue. Included in the offering\ngroup are the following:\nLehman Brothers, Chase Se\ncurities Corporation, First Na\ntional, Old Colony Corporation,\nBrown Brothers, Stone <fc Web\nster Blodget, Inc., E. H. Rollins\n<fe Sons, Kountze Brothers, A. B.\nLeach <fc Co., Inc., R. W. Press\nprich <fc Co., F. S. Moseley Co.,\nCommercial National Bank <Sc\nTrust Co., Stranahan, Harris\nOatis, and Lawrence, Stem\nCo.\nOther firms participating in\nclude Mercantile-Commerce Com\npany, Heller, Bruce Co., Wells\nFargo Bank <fc Trust Co., Mil\nwaukee Company, Mississippi Val\nley Company, Batchelder <fc Co.\nand Darby Co.\nPublic offering of the bonds\nwill be made today at prices to\nyield from 3.75 per cent to 4.40\nper cent, according to maturity.\nThe bonds are due serially Jan\nuary 1, 1932-1950, Inclusive.\nBaltimorean Named\nOn Ship Sale Board\nGeorge S. Jackson, Baltimore,\nyesterday was selected by Presi\ndent Hoover as a member of his\nspecial commission on ship sales,\nwhich is to report on the advisa\nbility of permitting the United\nStates Lines to purchase the\nAmerican Diamond and the Amer\nican France Lines.\nWith the selection of Jackson\nthere are now five members of\nthe commission. The others are:\nC. M. Woolley, Ira A. Campbell,\nE. N. Hurley and H. G. Dalton.\nPresident Hoover was undecided\nwhether he would name a sixth\nmember, or direct the commis\nsion of five to proceed.\nCommittee Favors\nCotton Price Probe\nThe Sheppard resolution, au\nthorizing an inquiry into recur\nring slumps in cotton prices, was\nfavorably reported by the Senate\nAgriculture Committee yesterday.\nThe resolution directed that\nthe Secretary of Agriculture con\nduct the inquiry, particularly as\nto the annual price declines of\nthe past four years.\nSilas Strawn Heads\nInternal. Chamber\nAppointment of Silas H. Strawn,\nof Chicago, as chairman of the\nAmerican section of the Inter\nnational Chamber of Commerce\nwas announced yesterday. He suc\nceeds Thomas W. Lamont, whose\nterm expirAi yesterday.\nColorado Southern\nSeeks Bond Issue\nThe Colorado Southern rail\nroad has requested the Inter\nstate Commerce Commission for\nauthority to issue and sell $20,-\n000,000 of General Mortgage, 4Vi\nper cent gold bonds. The pro\nceeds will be used to reimburse\nthe road\u2019s treasury for capital ex\npenditures.\nNational Dally\nBoard at any time.\nSince the Farm Board was estab\nlished, it has been necessary for\nthe Treasury to carry a consider\nably larger cash balance than at\nany time since the post-war re\nconstruction period.\nIn September the Treasury will\nretire $351,640,500 in 3% per cent\ncertificates, in December $483,341,-\n000 in 3*/< per cent certificates,\nand June 15, 1931, an issue of\n$429,373,000 in 2% per cent certifi\ncates. The present bond market\nindicates the Treasury would be\nable to reduce the rate of the new\nissue in September as compared\nwith that to be retired.\nIn operations of the public debt\nduring the next year, it is prob\nable a substantial reduction will\nbe possible in interest charges,\nfrom the abnormally high rates\nwhich prevailed during 1928 and\n1929, when the booming stock\nmarket absorbed most of the\nfunds available for investment.\nIn view of the probability of a\nsmall surplus for 1931, it is\nprobable the reduction of the pub\nlic debt will be the lowest of any\nyear since the war. During the\nyear ending June 30, the debt was\nreduced by $746,000,000 and stood\nat $16,185,209,000. This was a\nreduction of $10,411,000,000 since\nthe debt was at its peak August\n31, 1919.\nBULLY DISPELS\nPESSIMISM\nYesterday\u2019s rally in stocks was\nconsidered sufficient basis by\nmany brokers for the making of\ntrading commitments for a turn\non the upside. Pending the clear\ning up of the uncertainty over\nhanging the market it was con\nsidered best to defer investment\npurchases for the time being,\nhowever.\nIn view of the positive indica\ntion given yesterday of further\ntechnical recovery we believe that\nshort term traders are justified\nin making commitments covering\nthe next few days. Long pull\ncommitments may well be de\nferred awaiting a test of the mar\nket later in the month after cur\nrent technical strength has been\nexpended.\u2014OTlS CO.\nRegardless of current fluctua\ntions many sound stocks are un\ndoubtedly on the bargain counter\nand should eventually sell much\nhigher.\u2014TO\u00dfEY KIRK.\nRemain cautious and not too\nenthusiastic, but suggest taking\nadvantage of the technical up\ntrend which exists at the moment.\n\u2014HARRISS <fc VOSE.\nWe think current bearishness\nhas been overdone, and for that\nreason alone we expect the rally\nto carry further. We think it is\npremature to call this an area of\naccumulation.\nLisman Digest Views\nMarket Conditions\nThe first issue of Lisman Di\ngest, a monthly publication de\nvoted to the money, stock and\nbond markets, makes its appear\nance today under the auspices of\nF. J. Lisman Co., members of\nthe New York Stock Exchange.\nThe initial issue is featured by a\ndiscussion of \u201cEasy Money,\u201d\nwhich F. J. Lisman, the senior\nmember of the firm, defines as\nmoney when it really is selling\nat very high rates because at\nthat time the lender is less dis\ncriminating or more \u201ceasy\" with\nthe borrower. Other features are\nanalyses of the stock and bond\nmarkets as of the end of June,\na section entitled \"Diversifica\ntion\u201d which treats of Individual\ninvestments in a wide range of\nindustries, statements c leading\nmarket analysts, etc.\nSolvay to Spend\n$5,000,000 on Plant\nSYRACUSE, July 2.\u2014Five mil\nlion will be spent by the Solvay\nProcess Co., subsidiary of the Al\nlied Chemical <fc Dye Co., in en\nlarging and improving its plant\nhere. About $1,000,000 will be\nspent on an additional pipe line\nto bring brine to the factory.\nCrude Oil Output Up\n30,471 Bbls. Daily\nTULSA, Okla., July 2.\u2014Daily\naverage crude oil production in\nthe United States in the week\nended June 28, increased 30,471\nbarrels over the preceding week,\ntotaling 2,619,251 barrels daily,\nthe Oil and Gas Journal today\nestimated. Light oil output in\ncreased 17.383 barrels daily.\nWILKINS\" VOTESS4\nThe board of directors of the\nJohn H. Wilkins Company, local\ncoffee merchants, have declared\nthe regular senii-annual dividend\nof $4 a share on the outstand\ning preferred stock of the or\nganization. A dividend of $1.50 a\nshare on the outstanding com\nmon stock was also voted. Both\ndividends are payable on July 10.\nWEDNESDAY, JULY 9, I\u00ae3O\nSTEEL DEMAND\nPLANNED FDD'\nDY FIRMS\nLarger Concerns in Slack Pe\nriod Prepare for Future; Cut j\nin Surplus Seen by Experts\nDespite the recession in busi\nness activity, the American steel\nindustry is going ahead with plans\nfor increasing its potential out\nput, according to steel executives.\nThe capital investment in steel\nmanufacturing plants Is estimated\nat between $14,000,000,000 and\n$16,000,000,000. This amount wjllg\nbe increased substantially before\nthe end of the year.\nThe annual capacity of the\nsteel industry is rated at 62,265,\n270 tons of ingots. It is esti\nmated that within 12 months\nthis capacity will be expanded\nby 4,000,000 tons. In embarking\nupon such an expansion program\nwhen thd business outlook is un\ncertain the steel industry is fol\nlowing a policy it has observed\nin previous periods of depression.\nThe policy is grounded upon\nthe belief that the use of steel\nthroughout the world is steadily\nIncreasing, and that by carrying\nout plant expansion in times of\ndepression dislocation of produc\ntion is avoided when the industry\nis functioning at capacity. In\naddition, materials needed in en\nlargement may generally be pur\nchased at lower prices.\nMore than 1,000,000,000 tons of\nsteel has been produced in the\nUnited States since, the industry\nwas founded here more than a\ncentury ago. One-half of that\ntotal has been produced in the\nlast 12 years.\nThe largest production the in-1\ndustry has achieved in one year\nwas in 1929, when the steel ingot\noutput was 56,433,473 tons. There\nwould appear to be little need for\nexpanding the potential output of\nthe industry at this time. How-1\never, the steel industry\u2019s record\nover the last 30 years has been an\naverage expansion of 1.200,000\ntons a year. Output in 1929 was\nTELEPHONE\na. your.\nAgK News-Tips\nT\nThe Washington Times\nOR DISTRICT 5260\nI Between 6:30 A. M. and 6 P. M.\nHU SSO 00 in Cash\n111 EVERY WEEK\n\u25a0KW.I Offered for the Best\nEl NEWS-TIPS\nSee Complete Details in the\nr WASHINGTON TIMES\nOn Leave I\nf B\n\u2014Time\u00ab Staff Photo\nH. G. HOSKINSON\nVICE PRESIDENT of the\nRiggs National Bank who is va\ncationing at the Blue Ridge Rod\nand Gun Club.\nmore than five and one-half times\nas large as in 1900.\nIn the decade that began in\n1880 steel production totaled 21.-\n695,421 tons, or more than four\ntimes the amount produced in the\ni preceding 75 years. From 1890 to\n1900 the industry\u2019s output tripled,\nand in the decade beginning 1900\nit tripled again. From 1910 to\n1920 steel output doubled, while\nin the decade ended last Decem\nber 31 steel production increased\n20 per cent.\nThe output of steel has there\nfore shown a diminished rate cf\nincrease in the last 20 years.\nThere have been no signs, how\never. that the saturation point is\nbeing approached, according to\nsteel executives. When this point\nis reached, they declare, the in\ni dustrial prestige of the entire\nI country is likely to be aftected.\nCalifornia Output\nOs Crude Oil Drops\nThe California crude oil output\nin the week ended June 28 aver\nages 599,900 barrels daily. This\nwas a decrease of 4.100 from the\nprevious week, according to the\nCalifornia Oil World.\ngg\nNO SLUMP SEEN\nIN AMUSEMENT\nBUSINESS\nBarometer of Spending Power\n-of Country Experiencing\nOnly a Seasonal Decline\nTheaters, which, despite sensa\ntional declines in attendance,\nhave always been a good barom\neter of the spending power of\nthe country, are experiencing no\nmore than the usual letdown in\nbusiness that comes with warm\nweather, according to reports\nfrom the leading companies\nwhich operate large chains of\npicture houses. Executives in the\ntrade have taken this as an indi\ncation that in most parts of the\ncountry the readjustment in\nj business conditions made\nlarge progress.\ni It is conceded, however, that\nthe\" advent of talking pictures\nhas abolished any standard basis\nupon which comparisons can be\nmade. This new form of enter\ntainment had just got under way\n1 in 1929 when the usual summer\nslump in business would ordi\nnarily have occurred, but during\nthe hot months the theaters ex\nl perienced the best business they\never had had.\nThe novelty kept business up\nto a high point virtually through\nthe winter months. At the open\ning of this year, however, ;ne\nbusiness had assumed normal\ntrends, according to the motion\npicture companies and in com\nparison with years prior to 1929,\nthe seasonal letdown has been\nno more severe than in any nor\nmal year.\nWhile earnings of the com\npanies for specific quarters are\nnot a good guide to the amount\nof business being done, because\nexpenses are not evenly distributed\nover the year, executives point to\nj the profits of the various com\npanies In the early months of this\nyear as an indication of the spend\ning power of the nation.\n25","height":"30453","width":"24387"}}
